The really interesting thought

Embryology isn’t about organisms.

It’s about controlled emergence.

That’s exactly what the Pantheon has been moving toward.

Not storing finished thoughts.

Creating conditions under which new thoughts reliably emerge.

That changes the repository from an encyclopedia into something much closer to a semantic developmental system.

I think that’s “keeping it close” to biology in the most productive way. You’re not saying ideas are embryos. You’re borrowing the developmental principles:

* common “genome” (core operators),
* local signaling (context),
* differentiation (specialization),
* allostasis (maintaining function through change),
* inheritance (passing on developmental rules).

That keeps the analogy grounded while giving you a rich framework for thinking about how ideas grow rather than simply how they’re stored.